What are deployments ?

Deployments 
- manage stateless applications (no memory of sessions needed) )( frontend /backend )
- Is like a manager for your pods 
- Can scale up and down & multiple pods updated instantly if need 
- Instead creating pods 1by1 you tell the deployment how many pods to spin up 
- pods are interchangable so if one crashes deployment replaces
- Deployment + replica sets created together = manages number of pods for deployment 

Deployment stategies: 
- Supports rolling updates as it updates pods 1by1
- canary releases (send a small percentage of traffic to new pods)
- blue-green (switch all traffic at once)

Layers for the deployment ?
- Kube controller manager 
- Deployment controller 
- Deployment 
- Replica sets = maintains number of pods 
  
Example 1: 
Kube controller manager - controllers - deployment controller ( part of master mode + control plane)
- Compares state with ETCD (stores cluster state 5 pods )
- Looks over deployment and replaces the dead pod and spins up 
- Rolling update decommissions one pod at a time while spinning new one up 

Ways to create a deployment with replicas , ports / namespaces ?
- kubectl create deployment (name) —-image () — port= <> —replicas= <>
- kubectl create k8-deployment —image=nginx —replicas=2
- kubectl create deployment nginx-deployment --image=nginx --replicas=3 --namespace=new-namespace


What are replica sets ? 

Replica sets - simplest kuberntes pod controller resource 
- Maintain a given number of pods and if  one fails the replica sets with spin up a new instance to replace it 
- Similar to deployment but cant do rolling updates
- Not used as often as deployments are 
- Deployment + replica sets created together = manages number of pods for deployment 

